node.text:
honey, we’re nuts about @walgreens // #ad 

welcome to round two of olivia recommends snacks from #walgreens! here’s my second favorite (sorry, but still obsessed with sriracha ranch) flavor of nice! cashews: honey roasted. you all know i completely lose any sense of routine or adult behavior (saving money?? eating regular meals?? never heard of it) in the summer, but fortunately these are…
a. available in-store, online, or via pick-up at any walgreens
b. affordable compared to national brands like planters
c. easy to eat—i like to toss mine in greek yogurt with some berries in the morning for extra energy.

let me know in the comments which you’d choose between sriracha ranch or honey roasted—there might be something in it for one of you 😉

node.text:
snack queen reporting for duty 👑 // #ad @walgreens 

we all know there’s absolutely nothing i love more than spending all my money on food, but #walgreens has somehow tricked me into saving my pennies—up to $2 to be exact—when i choose nice! cashews over planters. they offer lots of fun flavors, and i’m currently working my way through this bag of sriracha ranch, which i will be repurchasing immediately to keep in my desk at work (but we’re not talking about back to school yet 🙃). you can pick some up for yourself at your local walgreens—try their pick-up option if you’re in a rush! happy snacking, everyone.

node.text:
can anyone believe they’ve let me live and work in chicago for two entire years? yikes! here i am with a book in a concerted effort to convince you that i do other things besides eat, drink, and decorate my apartment.

you know how sometimes you start something—a habit, a friendship, whatever—and it very quickly becomes a “how did i ever live without this?” situation? that’s how i feel about chicago. even just now, typing this out, i thought: two (2) years? that’s it? maybe that’s a function of living in covid dystopia, but even considering that, it feels like i’ve been here forever. chicago is loud and musical and messy and dramatic and beautiful and political and busy and fun. i can be all of those things, though not usually all at once, and so we fit, me and this city.

because I spent many years doing the opposite, i now believe really strongly in knowing who you are and doing at least a performance of independence to the best of your ability, but i also believe that we need connection in whatever form is meaningful to us, moment by moment. that means this is a letter not just to chicago, but to the people i rely on for connection. i love you. thank you for dancing with me and drinking too much wine with me and laughing at stupid tweets with me and picking out plants with me and crying with me (mostly just listening to me cry). i love you. did i say that already? who cares.

this is also, annoyingly, my 1,000th post, which feels stupid. i can’t imagine anything that could make this feel less serious than tossing social media into it, but i highly doubt i would even be where i am had it not wormed its way into my life however many years ago, so here we are.

i hope if you’re ever scared to do something, whether it’s moving across the country or picking a new hair color or living authentically or buying the stupid shoes, that you can trust yourself enough to do it. you deserve that.

LAST CHANCE✨ #keepingthewonderbook 

i am asked pretty regularly for teaching book recommendations, and I rarely have a good answer, but suddenly that problem has been solved because MY FRIENDS WROTE A BOOK! (my friends wrote a book??? what am i doing with my life?). if you’re a secondary teacher looking for tools to help make your instruction more…

• magical
• engaging
• joyful

then this is the professional development book made personal that you need as we head into another year of unknowns. plus, today is the last day to get a surprise wonder welcome gift when you order! just swipe up in my stories and follow the directions you see to get your copy + access your gift 💜
